05311nam a22006735i 9781978800212DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021046761  a97819788002127 a10.36019/97819788002122doi  a(DE-B1597)637948  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aE263.N5bL87 2022 4aE263.N5bL87 2022 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a974.9/03223/eng/202110121 aLurie, Maxine N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTaking Sides in Revolutionary New Jersey :bCaught in the Crossfire /cMaxine N. Lurie. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (282 p.) :b34 images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCERES: Rutgers Studies in History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tNote on the Text -- tChronology -- t1 Overview of the Revolution in New Jersey -- t2 Patriots Part I The Adamant and Determined -- t3 Patriots Part II In the Maelstrom -- t4 Straddlers, Trimmers, and Opportunists -- t5 The Society of Friends (Quakers) Pacifists and Participants -- t6 Loyalists Part I The Irreconcilables -- t7 Loyalists Part II Remained or Returned -- t8 Epilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe American Revolution in New Jersey lasted eight long years, during which many were caught in the middle of a vicious civil war. Residents living in an active war zone took stands that varied from “Loyalist” to “Patriot” to neutral and/or "trimmer" (those who changed sides for a variety of reasons). Men and women, Blacks and whites, Native Americans, and those from a wide variety of ethnic backgrounds, with different religious affiliations all found themselves in this difficult middle ground. When taking sides, sometimes family was important, sometimes religion, or political principles; the course of the war and location also mattered. Lurie analyzes the difficulties faced by prisoners of war, the refugees produced by the conflict, and those Loyalists who remained, left as exiles, or surprisingly later returned. Their stories are interesting, often dramatic, and include examples of those literally caught in the crossfire. They illustrate the ways in which this was an extremely difficult time and place to live. In the end more of the war was fought in New Jersey than elsewhere, resulting in the highest number of casualties, and a great deal of physical damage. The costs were high no matter what side individuals took. Taking Sides uses numerous brief biographies to illustrate the American Revolution’s complexity; it "es from documents, pamphlets, diaries, letters, and poetry, a variety of sources to provide insight into the thoughts and reactions of those living through it all. It focuses on people rather than battles and provides perspective for the difficult choices we make in our own times. Supplemental Instructor Resources for Taking Sides in Revolutionary New Jersey: Questions (https://d3tto5i5w9ogdd.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/19144155/Taking-Sides-Supplementary-Instructor-Resources-Questions.pdf) Bibliography (https://d3tto5i5w9ogdd.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2022/07/19144154/Taking-Sides-Supplementary-Instructor-Resources-Bibliography.pdf)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAmerican loyalistszNew JerseyvBiography. 0aQuakerszNew JerseyvBiography. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  ahistory, war, America, USA, American Revolution, Revolutionary War, American Revolutionary War, New Jersey, NJ, Loyalists, Patriots, Great Britain, biographies, Tories, Quakers, Society of Friends, Pacifism, military, military history, civil wa